{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3613db81-e625-41cb-80c3-4b87ff32ae52","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the recommended cross-platform tool for .NET performance tracing.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU trace (30 seconds is usually enough)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or convert to `.speedscope` format:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\nThen open it at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n### Alternative: PerfView\nFor deeper OS-level analysis (kernel + managed stacks), use **PerfView**:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for simplicity. Escalate to PerfView if you need kernel-level detail (GC, thread pool, I/O).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65e5e94f-7b2f-4139-b63d-caa192706389","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question — no code changes or repo exploration needed. I'll give a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":380,"requestId":"9431:180180:1860940:1BA7667:69E81DCD"},"id":"528b4814-ccc8-4f42-bc97-b14d29b1cad2","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:01:10.955Z","parentId":"f8918487-f0b5-4831-82fd-2620956e0314"}
